Residents in several Baltimore neighborhoods came up with a way to connect Tuesday night, even while practicing social distancing.

Residents in several Baltimore neighborhoods came up with a way to connect Tuesday night, even while practicing social distancing.The plan spread on Facebook neighborhood pages over the past day or so.The idea was to get on rooftops and have a good time, as a show of unity.Call it an isolation distraction or just a fun way to party at a distance, some residents in Patterson Park, Upper Fells Point and Canton came up with a way to share some love with their neighbors at the same time, but on their separate rooftops. "This is a good kind of escape from all the negative that's going on and bringing it back to the positive," said organizer Brittany North.North said she got the idea when she saw video of people on lockdown in Italy because of the coronavirus outbreak, gathering at windows and terraces every night -- singing and playing instruments. So she called on neighbors to get on their rooftops and stoops, still at a social distance but having fun and playing some music. "Because Baltimore has a lot of heart, I think it just represents how strong and connected we are, and even if we can't be around each other physically, we can at least from afar," North said.  "Without a moment to pause and be outside and be in the community and be surrounded by neighbors, we're all going to go a little crazy," said resident Abby Hopper. North picked the song "Dance My Pain Away," and although it got too chilly for many to stay out long, it's possible it will be the first of many. "A lot of people liked the idea of it. Longer term, the concept rings true to doing something together to be connected as a neighborhood, despite not being together physically," said Patrick Shea.Residents have also come up with what they're calling a "Virtual tip jar" to help out people in the service industry who aren't working right now.You can find a link to financially support workers here.             BALTIMORE
