Department of Agriculture issues spotted laternfly quarantine for Cecil, Harford counties
.W
The Maryland Department of Agriculture issued a spotted lanternfly quarantine Monday for all of Cecil and Harford counties.

The Maryland Department of Agriculture issued a spotted lanternfly quarantine Monday for all of Cecil and Harford counties. The quarantine is effective immediately and will restrict the movement of regulated articles within the quarantine zone that contain the spotted lanternfly in any of its life stages, including egg masses, nymphs and adults, officials said.According to officials, examples of "regulated articles" include landscaping, remodeling or construction waste; packing materials like wood boxes or crates; plants and plant parts; vehicles; and other outdoor items.The quarantine has been issued in an effort to control the spread of this invasive insect to other parts of the state, officials said.Following a 2019 survey season from the department, Cecil and Harford counties were found to have established populations of spotted lanternfly. Businesses, municipalities and government agencies that require the movement of any regulated item within or from the quarantine zone must have a permits, officials said. A permit can be obtained by taking a free online training course through PennState Extension. Upon completion of the course and an online exam, individuals will receive a permit.Officials said all spotted lanternfly permits for Virginia, Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Delaware are transferable and valid throughout the region — meaning a permit from any of these states can be used in Maryland. Maryland is currently in the process of developing its own training and permitting system for spotted lanternfly.Residents living within the quarantine zone are encouraged to be vigilant in containing the spread of spotted lanternfly. The spotted lanternfly poses a major threat to the region’s agricultural industries as it feeds on over 70 different types of plants and crops, including grapes, hops, apples, peaches, oak, pine and others. Originally from Asia, the spotted lanternfly is nonnative to the U.S., and was first detected in Berks County, Pennsylvania in the fall of 2014. As a known hitchhiker, the spotted lanternfly has spread to 14 counties within Pennsylvania, and also has confirmed populations in Delaware, Virginia, and New Jersey.A map of the quarantine zone can be viewed here.If you suspect you have found a spotted lanternfly, snap a picture of it, collect it, put it in a plastic bag, freeze it, and report it to the Maryland Department of Agriculture at DontBug.MD@maryland.gov. Dead samples from any life stage can be sent to the Maryland Department of Agriculture Plant Protection and Weed Management Program at 50 Harry S. Truman Parkway, Annapolis, MD 21401.More information about the spotted lanternfly can be found on the department’s website. For questions related to the quarantine, permitting, or treatment, please contact that Plant Protection and Weed Management Program at 410-841-5920.             BALTIMORE
