rus, Johns Hopkins University said it will transition to remote instruction for all classroom-based academic programs.In a statement sent Tuesday, JHU said it is encouraging undergraduate students not to return to campus from spring break next week and to plan to remain home through at least April 12."Remote undergraduate instruction will begin March 23. With the exception of clinical and laboratory-based programs or the equivalent, graduate instruction will also move course delivery to a remote format as quickly as possible," the university said.The university confirmed there are members of the JHU community, including several students, in the process of being tested for coronavirus. Officials are awaiting the results of those testsUniversity officials said they will continue to closely monitor the situation.Click here for a statement from the university.Morgan State UniversityMorgan State University said it has decided to cancel classes for the remainder of the week, as well as suspend all in-classroom instruction for two weeks after spring break.According to university officials, during the minimum two-week period after spring break, Morgan will implement online/remote learning instruction for all undergraduate and advanced degree students."At the end of the two-week period, we will reassess the situation to determine if further action is necessary. In addition, the University has elected to suspend all official business and student-related travel – both domestic and international," said MSU president David Wilson.The university said it will also cancel and/or reschedule a number of planned large crowd events on the campus, including an upcoming Open House on April 3.Morgan will remain open and operational during the week of spring break with the exception of March 20.During the spring break period, the resident halls will remain open to accommodate any student who does not wish to travel or leave the campus. On-campus accommodations, including access to dining, 