 we have to realize that after the tornado comes through is going to be tremendous economic damage to the state in its aftermath," Franchot said.Business owners told 11 News they are waiting for a potential closure order and wondering if they'll be able to come back."Hopefully, it'll end soon and we will find some medicine to fix this, but this is going to hurt everybody," said Eugenie Baghdadlian, with Cezanne Jewelers in Annapolis. "We don't know what's going to happen today and tomorrow. We're just holding on day by day."If Cezanne Jewelers closes, four full-time jobs would disappear.Maryland has 175,000 small businesses that make up 83% of the state's economy, according to the comptroller. "So once this virus is past us, we actually have an economy. Otherwise, we risk 25% unemployment. We are, unfortunately, predicting huge decreases in tax revenue and, most of all, my concern is the small businesses will never reopen after they close," Franchot said.It's known that layoffs have occurred; however the extent of jobless claims is unknown because numbers will not be available for this week. Federal officials asked its state counterparts to reveal nothing until next week.Baltimore mayor orders freeze on hiring, spending amid coronavirus pandemicBaltimore Mayor Jack Young released a statement Friday, saying he has instructed the Finance Department to immediately freeze all non-essential hiring and spending. On the hiring side, sworn public safety positions will be exempted. Those positions include police officers, paramedics, firefighters and EMTs, and sheriff's deputies. Agencies can request an exemption for other positions."From a budgeting standpoint, municipalities across the state, and throughout the nation, will need to be fiscally prudent as we navigate this unprecedented emergency," Young said in a statement. "The hiring and spending freeze represents a pair of necessary first steps to ensure that as revenues continue to decline, we remain in a position to quickly respond to the needs of our residents and first responders."According to the statement, the city's Finance Department, based on assumptions related to the pandemic, is forecasting sharp declines in a variety of city revenue sources, including the hotel tax, admissions tax, convention center receipts, parking-related revenues, traffic-camera revenues, income tax and others.​PHNjcmlwdCBpZD0iaW5mb2dyYW1fMF9kZWIyNWMzOC03OGU3LTQyOTgtODIxYS1kYzlmOWJlM2Y4ZWEiIHRpdGxlPSJNYXJ5bGFuZCBjb3JvbmF2aXJ1cyBjYXNlcyIgc3JjPSJodHRwczovL2UuaW5mb2dyYW0uY29tL2pzL2Rpc3QvZW1iZWQuanM/REVjIiB0eXBlPSJ0ZXh0L2phdmFzY3JpcHQiPjwvc2NyaXB0Pg==             ANNAPOLIS, Md.
