ngs -- everywhere are to be canceled or postponed. When out in public, practice social distancing -- keeping at least 6 feet apart from others.  Why social distancing works . DONATE MASKS, OTHER SUPPLIES Four locations are open around the state to accept donations of specialized medical equipment and some cleaning supplies to support the Maryland Emergency Management Agency and other state agencies --  learn more here . Businesses or organizations offering capabilities, personnel and equipment can email  psector@maryland.gov .  BUSINESSES On March 23, the governor ordered all  nonessential businesses to close . Interpretive guidance from the Governor's Office of Legal Counsel: COVID19-04  ( En español ) -- Businesses that may remain open  COVID19-05  -- Additional businesses that may remain open, guidance for retail COVID19-06  -- Additional businesses, staff access for nonessential businesses COVID19-11  -- Barber Shops and Salons are Generally Closed  The Maryland Departments of Labor and Commerce have established a one-stop portal for businesses and employees impacted by the coronavrius  here . Small businesses can  apply for federal disaster loans from the Small Business Administration . HEALTH COVERAGE To enroll in health coverage, go to  MarylandHealthConnection.gov  and select the "coronavirus emergency special enrollment period." Free consumer assistance is available by calling 855-642-8572 from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. weekdays. Marylanders can enroll starting March 16 through April 15. FOOD STAMPS (SNAP), MEDICAL ASSISTANCE, WIC FAQ for SNAP and medical assistance and other social services Information on WIC  -- nutrition program for women, infants and children, administered through Maryland Department of Health CHILD CARE/SCHOOLS Beginning March 27,  child-care facilities were ordered to close , except those that have been approved to serve essential personnel.  Tap here for list of child-care providers open to essential personnel Distance learning :  Educational