ns."Hogan said additional enforcement efforts will be taken to disperse gatherings."Beginning today, even further and more aggressive enforcement actions will be taken by state and local authorities to disperse these gatherings," Hogan said. "Unless you have a critical reason to leave, you should stay home."Hogan's order comes after the state already took sweeping measures to close schools, malls and entertainment venues, among other locations. He's also establishing an alternate care site at the Baltimore Convention Center and Hilton Hotel.The governor announced Maryland has seen a 678% spike in positive coronavirus cases since last week. The Maryland Department of Health announced Monday that the state has 288 confirmed cases of coronavirus, much of it centered in the D.C. suburbs."Our first priority is saving the lives of thousands of Marylanders," Hogan said. "It's going to take all of us working together to save thousands of lives."Watch: Gov. Hogan announces new directivesTESTING: The governor enacted an emergency order to authorize a fast-track process to bring more testing capacity online without U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval to shorten a process that would ordinarily take several months.The Maryland Department of Health is issuing an order to require health-care providers to prioritize tests for hospitalized and chronic-care patients, symptomatic first responders and symptomatic nursing home patients.The governor said four Motor Vehicle Administration sites are ready for drive-through testing as soon as the state gets the test kits and the personal protective equipment necessary to do it.Also, $5 million is being used to incentivize local production of crucial supplies, including, facemasks, ventilators and personal protective equipment.BUSINESS: With so many businesses now closed and so many workers not collecting paychecks, the Hogan administration is rolling out a $175 million move to ensure the state's economy survives the coronavirus pandemic.Small and medium-sized businesses make up 83% of the Maryland economy."We're also facing another huge battle against the potential of tremendous economic harm," Hogan said. "We will have your backs in the weeks ahead, and we will do everything we can to help get you back on your feet and to help all of your employees recover."|| LINK: Maryland Coronavirus (COVID-19) Information for Business ||The economic arsenal announced Monday includes $75 million for the COVID-19 Emergency Relief Loan Fund, $50 million for the COVID-19 Emergency Relief Grant Fund and $7 million for the COVID-19 Layoff Aversion Fund.Businesses and nonprofits with under 50 full- and part-time employees will be eligible, and loans will range up to $50,000 and grants up to $10,000, according to the governor's office.The governor has allocated $5 million and the Maryland Department of Labor has allocated $2 million to collaboratively launch the COVID-19 Layoff Aversion Fund.A total of $7 million in funds will be available to provide flexible rapid response services to proactively support businesses and workers undergoing economic stresses due to COVID-19."Our businesses must survive and our people must have jobs they can return to when things return to normal," Maryland Commerce Secretary Kelly Schulz said. "We are in uncharted waters now. The situation is unlike anything we've seen in our lifetimes, but we will get through this."PRICE GOUGING: Hogan has signed an emergency order to protect families from price gouging on everyday household items and essentials. Retailers who attempt to exploit this crisis will be prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law, Hogan said.NATIONAL GUARD: Hogan has directed the Maryland National Guard and the Maryland Department of Health to collaborate with Prince George's County and the University of Maryland Medical System on a pilot assessment location at FedEx Field in Landover.On Friday, Hogan activated the Maryland National Guard to help hospitals in setting up