e next one-two days and then touching their face," he said. "That I think is incredibly empowering," Price said, adding that he knows he won’t get the disease because he knows how to protect himself.The "vast, vast, vast" majority of transmission is by droplet, meaning hands to face. The droplet can come from an infected person's mouth and go to hand or surface. That, in turn, is very quickly taken up by another person and put on their face.It happens with sustained contact with someone who has this disease (where the vast majority has fever or aches) or someone who is about to get the disease, meaning someone in the next one-two days is going to develop symptoms of the disease.People get it through sustained contact, such as shaking one’s hand then touching your face.HOW EFFECTIVE IS CLEANING YOUR HANDS AGAINST THE DISEASE? Cleaning one’s hands and not touching your face will help 99% of cases, he said.When he leaves his apartment and touches an elevator button or door handle with his hand, he uses hand sanitizer."Everything we touch, we clean our hands," he said. "Become a hand Nazi." He described the coronavirus as a wimp that dies as soon as you disinfect it. He also said a small drop of hand sanitizer will do the job.SHOULD YOU USE A FACE MASK?You don’t need a medical mask. These masks that people are wearing are not protecting them from the disease, and front-line medical workers need them. You don’t need a wild supply. The general community has zero need for N95 masks.But masks or bandanas can be helpful for you to stop touching your face; if you leave your house and wear a mask, it can help. He encourages people to wear a mask — not because you’re going to get COVID-19 that way. But it will train you not to touch your face and show people you’re serious about the disease.WHAT ABOUT SOCIAL DISTANCING?Stay three to six feet away from people.When you go to the pharmacy, you don’t have to wait directly in front of someone. You can stand a few steps back.If you go to grocery store, if you touch cart, just clean the handle; if you see people around, don’t touch them.  He also stressed the importance of shrinking your social circle. He recommended finding your isolation group, such as three or four people or your family, and setting boundaries.WHAT DO YOU DO IF YOU GET THE DISEASE?The vast majority of spread throughout the world is through home and family transmission.You shouldn’t be scared to stay at home with your family with a fever if you have COVID-19. You can have COVID in your house and be safe and not have everyone else get it.If you have COVID-19 and you’ve recovered for seven days and you’re feeling better, you can return to your family’s life.If you’re able, have the person who is sick in a separate room and with their own bathroom; have person who is sick wear a mask if they have to interact with their family. (An exception to this is if you have someone vulnerable in your family, such as someone who recently had chemotherapy or is 95 years old, you should find another living arrangement.)WHAT DO I DO IF I HAVE A MILD COLD?If you have a cold or feel like you’re getting sick, take precautions like you have COVID-19 for one to two days. If after that time you feel better and it’s like the thousands of other colds you’ve had, you can return to normal activities.WHEN DO YOU GO TO THE HOSPITAL?"If you’re feeling short of breath, come to the hospital. … It’s not, ‘I have a fever.’ It’s not, ‘I think I have COVID-19.’ It’s not, ‘I can’t stop having these body aches.’ It’s, ‘I feel short of breath when I get up to go to the bathroom."Those people should be evaluated at a hospital.A lot of people who come to his emergency room are sent home so they can recover on their own for three to five days.Of all people infected, about 10 percent need to go to hospital because they’re short of breath. Of those, about one to 3% require admission to an intensive care unit and put on a ventilator. The vast majority of people put on ventilator come off the ventilator, which happens seven to 10 days later."Going to the hospital is not a death sentence," he said. "It’s a safe place for you to be."SHOULD I GET TESTED?Price thinks it depends on the availability of testing in your home.If you have clear access to testing, it’s a good idea. Because when it’s negative, you can have full interaction with your community. But if there’s very rare testing, don’t try to jump the line.WHO DOES THIS DISEASE AFFECT? WHAT ABOUT NEWBORNS AND KIDS? There's been almost no disease among children from ages zero to 14.Outside of that age group, you can end up on ventilator. The younger you are, the less likely that is to happen. The older you are, the more likely it is to happen. But we see young people who get sick and older people who do just fine. IS IT SAFE TO GO ON A RUN OR WALK?Yes, even if you’re in a city. Just follow the rules with hand sanitizer. Don’t touch your face. Don’t come into three to six feet of people.  SHOULD YOU DISINFECT GROCERY ITEMS?The general answer is no.If you live in New York City where there’s a lot of contact, it can be reasonable to leave takeout outside one's door and pick it up with a glove.But don’t high-five or shake a delivery person’s hand.He doesn’t think routine groceries need to be wiped down.IS IT OK TO GET COFFEE AT A DRIVE-THRU?It depends. If you can safely interact and follow the rules with hand sanitizer, it's OK. His general sense is to make coffee at home.IF YOU RETURN HOME, SHOULD YOU THEN WASH YOUR CLOTHES ONCE YOU GET BACK?Absolutely not. That’s a recommendation for health care providers.IF YOU GET SICK, HOW LONG SHOULD YOU WAIT TO GO TO THE DOCTOR OR HOSPITAL?Don’t go unless you’re short of breath, such as due to walking or sitting. If you have a fever, stay home.With telehealth, if you feel sick and you’re a little nervous, there are an army of doctors waiting to help.SHOULD YOU USE IBUPROFEN WITH A FEVER?Research suggests that the inflammation could be worse, so if you have a fever, take Tylenol.WHAT DOES TREATMENT LOOK LIKE?All patients look exactly the same: They have a cough and fever.When they get sick, they are short of breath. When they can’t walk to the bathroom, then they’re put on a ventilator. Around seven-10 days later, they’re taken off a ventilator.Many are scared. Medical staff tell patients they’re being put on ventilators so they can be taken off them.ARE HOSPITALS ACCEPTING HOMEMADE MASKS?The main role for a homemade mask should be for you to use so you can give manufactured face masks to medical providers who need them.HOW LONG WILL THIS LAST?He thinks social distancing will be needed for months to possibly up to a year. He thinks based on the experience from Wuhan, Singapore and South Korea is to flatten the curve so hospitals don’t get overwhelmed. There could be a second small spike when people become more relaxed.                        A New York City physician gave tips on how to protect you and your family as the coronavirus outbreak continues. Dr. Dave Price of New York Presbyterian-Weill Cornell Medical Center provided the information. His hospital has been converted to almost exclusively help COVID-19 patients, he said.                              Advertisement                       “I don’t want you guys to be scared,” he said in a  video call , which was uploaded on and around March 22. “We’re three months into this in the medical world and we understand this disease.” Above video: Officials are telling Americans to stay home to stop the spread of COVID-19 He noted how the key way the virus spreads is through hand-to-face contact, and he also answered questions. He also discussed how and when to use hand sanitizer, which is a secondary way to keep your hands clean. (The  Centers for Disease Control and Prevention notes  one should wash one's hands for 20 seconds due to COVID-19, but if soap and water are unavailable, use a sanitizer.)  Here are Price's remarks, summarized and shortened. WHAT DO