he world is through home and family transmission. You shouldn’t be scared to stay at home with your family with a fever if you have COVID-19. You can have COVID in your house and be safe and not have everyone else get it. If you have COVID-19 and you’ve recovered for seven days and you’re feeling better, you can return to your family’s life. If you’re able, have the person who is sick in a separate room and with their own bathroom; have person who is sick wear a mask if they have to interact with their family. (An exception to this is if you have someone vulnerable in your family, such as someone who recently had chemotherapy or is 95 years old, you should find another living arrangement.) WHAT DO I DO IF I HAVE A MILD COLD? If you have a cold or feel like you’re getting sick, take precautions like you have COVID-19 for one to two days. If after that time you feel better and it’s like the thousands of other colds you’ve had, you can return to normal activities. WHEN DO YOU GO TO THE HOSPITAL? "If you’re feeling short of breath, come to the hospital. … It’s not, ‘I have a fever.’ It’s not, ‘I think I have COVID-19.’ It’s not, ‘I can’t stop having these body aches.’ It’s, ‘I feel short of breath when I get up to go to the bathroom." Those people should be evaluated at a hospital. A lot of people who come to his emergency room are sent home so they can recover on their own for three to five days. Of all people infected, about 10 percent need to go to hospital because they’re short of breath. Of those, about one to 3% require admission to an intensive care unit and put on a ventilator. The vast majority of people put on ventilator come off the ventilator, which happens seven to 10 days later. "Going to the hospital is not a death sentence," he said. "It’s a safe place for you to be." SHOULD I GET TESTED? Price thinks it depends on the availability of testing in your home. If you have clear access to testing, it’s a good idea. Because when it’s negative, you can have full interaction with your community.  But if there’s very rare testing, don’t try to jump the line. WHO DOES THIS DISEASE AFFECT? WHAT ABOUT NEWBORNS AND KIDS?  There's been almost no disease among children from ages zero to 14. Outside of that age group, you can end up on ventilator. The younger you are, the less likely that is to happen. The older you are, the more likely it is to happen. But we see young people who get sick and older people who do just fine.  IS IT SAFE TO GO ON A RUN OR WALK? Yes, even if you’re in a city. Just follow the rules with hand sanitizer. Don’t touch your face. Don’t come into three to six feet of people.   SHOULD YOU DISINFECT GROCERY ITEMS? The general answer is no. If you live in New York City where there’s a lot of contact, it can be reasonable to leave takeout outside one's door and pick it up with a glove. But don’t high-five or shake a delivery person’s hand. He doesn’t think routine groceries need to be wiped down. IS IT OK TO GET COFFEE AT A DRIVE-THRU? It depends. If you can safely interact and follow the rules with hand sanitizer, it's OK. His general sense is to make coffee at home. IF YOU RETURN HOME, SHOULD YOU THEN WASH YOUR CLOTHES ONCE YOU GET BACK? Absolutely not. That’s a recommendation for health care providers. IF YOU GET SICK, HOW LONG SHOULD YOU WAIT TO GO TO THE DOCTOR OR HOSPITAL? Don’t go unless you’re short of breath, such as due to walking or sitting. If you have a fever, stay home. With telehealth, if you feel sick and you’re a little nervous, there are an army of doctors waiting to help. SHOULD YOU USE IBUPROFEN WITH A FEVER? Research suggests that the inflammation could be worse, so if you have a fever, take Tylenol. WHAT DOES TREATMENT LOOK LIKE? All patients look exactly the same: They have a cough and fever. When they get sick, they are short of breath. When they can’t walk to the bathroom, then they’re put on a ventilator. Around seven-10 days later, they’re taken off a ventilator. Many are scared. Medi