Will taking the right health supplements boost your immune system and help prevent you from getting the novel coronavirus? It's a question Americans are asking daily as confirmed cases climb with each passing day.To get a better understanding, Mark Albert spoke with Dr. Aisha Terry of George Washington University, to see what supplements, if any, can help prevent or treat COVID-19."Will taking supplements to build the immune system help ward off the coronavirus?" Albert asked. "In particular, echinacea, vitamin C? What is the science on that? What do you know on that?""Well, we're lucky in that there have been significant studies in the past on using various over-the-counter agents and vitamins and the like in terms of boosting our immune system," Terry said. "Not necessarily specific to COVID-19, but in terms of other types of viral illnesses." Terry also said there has been data suggesting the use of vitamin C could boost the immune system, and more data pointing to vitamin D possibly boosting lung capacity and lung health as well."And so I think that, you know, the over-the counter vitamins to boost our immune systems, as long as they're taken in accordance with what the directions say as far as the amount and the frequency, there's likely no harm in taking those items to try to boost our immune systems," Terry said. While supplements can be beneficial, Terry was quick to point out diet and exercise are also key components of health."Additionally, remember, it's important to eat, right?" Terry said. "Exercise, you know, meditate, make sure that mentally we're as healthy as we can be, because those actions also play a big role in keeping us healthy and keeping our immune system strong."The FDA last month issued a warning about dietary supplements if they're falsely marketed as a cure for COVID-19.            As of now, no FDA-approved treatment exists.                        Will taking the right health supplements boost your immune system and help prevent you fro