Without classes, some high school students answer call to work at Wisconsin polling site
.W
Concerns over coronavirus kept many of Wisconsin's elderly poll workers at home, which led one city to call on a previously untapped resource: high school students, who are less susceptible to coronavirus complications.

Concerns over coronavirus kept many of Wisconsin's elderly poll workers at home, which led one city to call on a previously untapped resource: high school students, who are less susceptible to coronavirus complications. Many of them answered the call and worked Tuesday in the city of Brookfield's only polling location, the new convention center. Brookfield Central sophomore Madeline Beug-Hoffman said her parents were supportive, and somewhat concerned, about her filling an important Election Day role for the city of Brookfield."They said they didn't have enough poll workers and that they needed help because the coronavirus affects the elderly most, so they needed people to come volunteer and work the polls," Beug-Hoffman said."Usually I'm the youngest one, so yeah, I do like it," long-time poll worker Tim Gramling said. "It's good to see a younger group come through."This time around, some of the workers aren't even old enough to vote."It feels like you're actually giving back to the community in a big way," Brookfield East junior Langston Ford said. "I think kids are motivated because they want the elderly to stay home," Brookfield East junior Natalie Karrels said. The students said they're learning important lessons even with schools closed by COVID-19."I think it's good to be a public service or poll worker, and I'm really interested in government, so this is a way to get behind the scenes and see how things work," Karrels said. The Brookfield mayor said there are five members of the National Guard at the one Brookfield polling place and twice as many high school students.              BROOKFIELD, Wis.
